Our cosmic visitor is the giant asteroid 2014 JO25 .
There are billions, perhaps more, of giant asteroids wandering around the solar system that could have serious consequences if they hit.
These objects, which can have closed or open orbits left over from the formation of the Sun, can sometimes pass by the Earth.
2014 JO25, a 650-meter-diameter asteroid, is one such visitor and will pass within 1.75 million kilometers of Earth at its closest approach today at 14:24.
This kind of news is becoming more and more frequent.
This is mainly due to improvements in observation techniques and instruments.
We'll be able to identify smaller asteroids that we couldn't identify before.
Last January, for example, an asteroid the size of a school bus passed within about a quarter of a million miles [250,000 km] of the earth.
And what's even more interesting is that the asteroid was spotted just a few days before the flyby.
So there could be other cosmic buses coming at us right now.
Imagine if you got the news that an asteroid 20 meters in diameter was going to hit right in the middle of your neighborhood.
Well, asteroids that size probably won't destroy your neighborhood, but they'll probably blow out the windows of every building.
This will be caused by the shock waves from the asteroid exploding in the atmosphere.
For example, the asteroid that hit Russia in 2013 was this size, and it was enough to shatter the windows of buildings in several cities.
But if you're in the neighborhood of an asteroid that's 100 meters in diameter, you're advised to go at least 50 kilometers away from your neighborhood.
Criteria such as the size of the asteroid and the angle of impact determine the depth of the crater and the damage caused by the impact.
Let's look at a few scenarios based on simulations by the European Space Agency.
If a 100-meter-wide asteroid were to hit the Earth at a 45-degree angle at a speed of 60 kilometers per second, it would create a crater about 250 meters deep and 1,200 meters wide.
The impact is equivalent to an earthquake of magnitude 6 on the Richter scale, and you'll get third-degree burns on your body even if you're 10 kilometers away from the point of impact.
30 miles away, they'll be looking at smashed windows.
It's even more depressing if it's hit by a mile-wide asteroid.
If such an asteroid were to hit the Earth at the same angle and velocity, it would leave a crater about 2,000 feet [600 m] deep and eight miles [12 km] in diameter.
I mean, an entire neighborhood could be turned into a crater and instantly disappear.
Because of the heat from the impact, you can get third-degree burns on your body even if you're 60 miles away from the point of impact.
The impact was equivalent to an earthquake of magnitude 8 on the Richter scale.
The damage caused by an asteroid depends not only on the chemical composition of the asteroid but also on the rock composition of the area it hits.
The above values refer to a scenario in which a hard rock-like asteroid crashes into a region of sedimentary rocks.
If the asteroid is made mostly of iron and hits a surface formed by cooling lava, the crater will triple in size and the resulting disaster will multiply.
And 66 million years ago, something even worse happened to the dinosaurs, when they were wiped out by an asteroid about six miles across.
75% of marine and terrestrial life was instantly wiped out by the asteroid impact.
If an asteroid as big as the one that wiped out the dinosaurs was headed for Earth, the safest option would be to leave the planet.
Tons of stuff falls to Earth from space every day.
Most of it burns up in the atmosphere.
Some meteorites large enough burn up in the atmosphere, causing flares commonly known as starbursts.
Let's end with another piece of good news.
Studies indicate that an asteroid large enough to cause serious destruction is not expected to hit the Earth for the next 300 to 400 years.
As creatures who live an average of 70 years, I'm sure you're relieved.
