Human rights group issues travel warning for Missouri.
The National Association for the Advancement of Colored People has issued a travel warning for people of color in Missouri due to the state's discriminatory policies and racist attacks.
The group's statement reads: "The state of Missouri NAACP Travel Advisory Notice, effective August 28, 2017, advises African-American travelers, visitors, and Missourians to exercise special caution and extreme caution when traveling throughout the state as outlined therein, due to recent suspicious, race-based events occurring throughout the state".
The NAACP said that a new Missouri law makes it harder for people to win discrimination lawsuits, but also that the state's law enforcement practices disproportionately target minorities, which was influential in the group issuing this travel warning.
"There are human rights violations happening to people.
They're being stopped, beaten and killed because of the color of their skin", Rod Chapel, president of the Missouri NAACP, told the Kansas City Star.
"We're hearing complaints at a rate we've never heard before".
This is the first time the association has issued such a warning for a state in the United States.
The group cited racist slurs against black students at the University of Missouri and the death of Tory Sanders, a black man from Tennessee.
Sanders died under suspicious circumstances earlier this year after he ran out of gas while driving across the state and was taken into custody by Missouri police without being charged with a crime.
The advisory also points to a recent report from the Missouri Attorney General's Office showing that black drivers in the state are 75 percent more likely to be stopped than white drivers.
Chapel said, "The advisory is for people to be vigilant and to warn their family, friends and co-workers that they may be in Missouri".
"People need to be prepared, whether it's bringing bail money or notifying relatives that they're passing through the state".
In Missouri, according to the latest figures from the FBI's hate crime reporting program, 100 hate crimes were committed in 2015, which puts the state 16th in the country for the number of similar violations.
The travel warning is also a response to a new Missouri law that makes it harder to sue a business for discrimination in housing or employment.
Previously, the American Civil Liberties Union (ACLU) issued travel advisories for Texas and Arizona after those states' local governments passed immigration enforcement laws ordering the arrest of people for immigration violations; the ACLU says this will increase enforcement by race.
Travel warnings are usually issued by the State Department for other countries, but recently advocacy groups have resorted to this practice in response to a number of laws and trends within the United States.
