Blocking critics on Facebook: Don't run for public office if you can't take criticism from voters
The father of our country knew a thing or two about getting negative press.
Americans loved George Washington, but it wasn't long before newspapers began heavily criticizing him for everything from domestic policy to his political principles.
Of course, he was bothered by the criticism.
But he did not silence his critics.
Because in 1783, Washington said, "Freedom of speech can be taken away and we can be led stupidly and silently to slaughter".
Which brings me to Maryland Governor Larry Hogan, who needs to work harder to be more like Washington.
Hogan's staff blocked and deleted at least 450 posts on his official Facebook page.
The American Civil Liberties Union sued him earlier this week.
The governor's staff dismissed the case as frivolous, and online comments were full of "who cares?" reactions.
A lot of people said, "It's just Facebook".
But this is important.
It's especially important when you have someone like Hogan.
This is a Republican governor who's surprisingly popular in an overwhelmingly Democratic state.
He has the second highest approval rating of any of the 50 governors in the country.
Hogan is not a reactionary firecracker.
He showed great skill in leading his state and a firm commitment to principle.
He was also quite adept at using Facebook as his primary tool for connecting with his constituents, jokingly presenting his hairless head after chemotherapy.
So blocking people from visiting the governor's page, which is a public forum that is officially sanctioned and run by staffers paid for by the people's tax dollars, is unnecessary and ultimately dangerous.
In an interview with The Washington Post, Hogan's spokeswoman Amelia Chasse defended the governor's actions, arguing that blocking comments is nothing more than editing them.
But it's very easy to use images of trolls or spammers or hate-mongers verbally attacking people online.
The Post spoke to some of the real people who were blocked by Hogan.
And these are just real people talking to their elected leaders: a teacher, a business owner and a pastor; not trolls.
They all said their comments were disrespectful, inconsiderate and abusive.
In his post, the pastor quoted from the Bible, appealing to Hogan's Catholic faith.
Lakshmi Sarma Ramani, a lawyer from Bowie, Maryland, was not hateful, but she asked about hate crimes.
He wrote in the comment section of The Post's story, "I politely commented that I was disappointed by the lack of response to his hate crimes and other recent news".
"I also don't like the idea that when many people comment on the same issue, it is immediately dismissed by some as a so-called collective effort rather than a large group of concerned citizens".
What the governor's staff calls a "concentrated spam attack" others will probably call "advocacy".
The age of Facebook makes it easy to easily appropriate a message by blocking a dissenter or deleting a negative message.
It's much cleaner than the old days when staff were sent out to collect and burn critical newspapers or to arrest and silence protesters.
But, digitally, that's exactly what's happening.
Hogan isn't the first public official to be criticized for disabling Facebook and other social media.
President Trump is being sued by Twitter users who have been blocked from his Twitter feed.
One of the landmark rulings on this issue came from Virginia last week.
The Loudoun County Board of Supervisors violated the First Amendment when it banned a voter from Facebook, according to U.S. District Judge James C. Cacheris in Alexandria.
In Kentucky, Governor Matt Bevin (Republican) was visited by the ACLU for his use of Facebook and Twitter.
It shouldn't be that hard.
In Washington's time, the era of affordable mail had a very similar effect to the Internet.
Between 1775 and 1800, the number of newspapers quadrupled, and anonymous letter writers eroded his leadership.
Even then, Washington had its unnamed trolls.
People using pseudonyms such as Juricola, Valerius, Belisarius and Portius all wrote letters to newspapers denouncing Washington's decisions.
According to the George Washington Papers Project, an online collection of historical documents, petitions criticizing his position on the Treaty of Amity, Commerce, and Navigation with Britain overwhelmed the office.
But he didn't shut them up.
Freedom of speech, freedom of dissent, and freedom of assembly are at the very foundation of our nation.
And real leadership means recognizing that.
