An existing movement propagating independence from Dutch rule quickly directed its anger at the Jakarta government, which maintained tight control over the region, banning foreign journalists or rights watchdog organizations.
In 2003, the region was officially split into Papua and West Papua, with independent Papua New Guinea occupying the eastern half of the island.
Enarotali is as remote as it is desolate, involving a 90-minute flight from the regional capital, Jayapura, to Nabire and a stomach-churning five-hour drive in a rented car.
There is no public transportation.
The town of 19,000 people contains wooden houses surrounded by bamboo fences, wrinkled iron roofs transformed by rust into various shades of yellowish brown.
Few Indonesians have traveled here, let alone journalists, and almost no foreigners.
Before the arrival of Christian missionaries, the Mee Pago Papuans worshipped a god called Uga Tamee.
There have been other changes.
"We were not used to wearing these clothes", says Degei, referring to her brightly colored, handwoven jacket, dark shirt, and bright skirt.
"Before, we only wore leaves on our bodies".
Papua is the poorest region in Indonesia, with 28 percent of the people living below the poverty line and some of the worst child mortality and literacy rates in Asia.
But it's also the golden land of Indonesia.
Grasberg, the world's largest and most profitable gold mine, owned by Phoenix-based Freeport McMoran, is just 60 miles from Paniai, a mountainous region the size of New Jersey and home to 153,000 people.
In 2015 alone, Freeport extracted approximately $3.1 billion worth of gold and copper.
In addition, Papua has an estimated $78 billion in timber reserves.
Yet, these riches, a source of misery for Papuans, provide a stifling existence for Indonesia's powerful military.
A 2005 New York Times investigation reported that Freeport paid local military personnel and units approximately $20 million between 1998 and 2004, including up to $150,000 to a single officer.
The Papuans' call for greater autonomy threatens this golden goose and their rights are being ruthlessly infringed.
According to rights activists, more than 500,000 Papuans have been killed by the Indonesian military since 1969, and thousands more have been raped, tortured and imprisoned.
Mass killings in the highlands of Papua in the 1970s amounted to genocide, according to the Asian Human Rights Commission.
Indonesian police arrested more than 3,900 peaceful protesters in the region last year alone.
The Archdiocese of Brisbane's 2016 report "We Will Lose Everything" includes testimonies of atrocities committed in the previous year, including extrajudicial executions, torture (rape and electrocution are particularly popular, according to another report), and the brutal suppression of peaceful demonstrations.
"It is difficult to calculate the number of victims because there are incidents every week", says Andreas Harsono, Indonesia researcher for Human Rights Watch.
As Papua's resources brought settlers from elsewhere in Indonesia, the pressures increased.
The region's population of 3.5 million is 83 percent Christian, but the demographics are changing as Muslim migrants from Indonesia's populous islands of Java, Borneo, Sumatra and Sulawesi arrive for economic reasons.
Javanese warung buffets sell gado-gado, served with roasted chicken and vegetables mixed with peanut sauce.
The locals are having a hard time competing.
"The migrants sell chicken and vegetables cheaper than the local Papuans in the traditional markets", explains Abeth You, 24, a native of Paniai who moved to the regional capital, Jayapura, for work.
"This has caused the indigenous Papuans, the Papuan mama-mama's (women), to lose their market".
Indonesian President Joko Widodo, better known as Jokowi, promised to address inequalities and rights violations in Papua during his 2014 election campaign.
The former carpenter received the votes of 27 of Papua's 29 districts, including Panaia, as he made his way to the presidential palace in Jakarta.
But little has changed in Papua, and today the local people feel cheated.
"Our hearts are broken because we voted for Jokowi in 2014 with the expectation that he would fulfill our hope that justice would be restored", says You.
In fact, Paniai's worst was just two months after Jokowi took office in October.
On December 7, 2014, a group of 11 children were outside singing Christmas carols in front of a bonfire in Enarotali when two Indonesian soldiers on a motorcycle drove through the darkness.
The frightened children told them to turn on their headlights.
One of the soldiers was offended by their manner and later returned with four soldiers, according to local priest Yavedt Tebai.
The victims and witnesses said that the group of soldiers, who had been drinking, chased them and beat them with the butts of their rifles.
Then one of the soldiers opened fire on the group of children.
One of the boys, 16-year-old Yulianus Yeimo, was beaten so badly that he fell into a coma.
A few hours later, the nearby government election commission building was set on fire, and events escalated the next day.
Some 1,000 Papuan men, women, and children gathered on a soccer field in front of the local police station and military command center to demand justice.
They carried ceremonial hunting bows and performed the waita dance of the Mee Pago tribe of Papua.
Some protesters began throwing stones at the police and the military garrison.
As tensions mounted, soldiers were ordered over the intercom: "If the crowd offers more than three times resistance, shoot to kill".
Jeremiah Kayame, 56, the head of the Kego Koto neighborhood in Enarotali, saw the approaching danger and pleaded for calm, urging the crowd to return home.
No one was willing to listen.
"As I turned around, I was suddenly shot in the left wrist", he told TIME from the porch of his brightly painted wooden home.
Kayame still doesn't know who fired the shots, but he says the bullet came from a recovered military rifle.
"It was crowded, many shots were fired", he adds.
According to his cousin, who witnessed the attacks, local man Alfius Youw was shot three times.
"I ran to him and examined his body to make sure it was him", Yohanes, who like many Indonesians is known only by one name, told TIME gloomily.
"I saw her die... and I kissed her".
Papua Police Chief Inspector General Yotje Mende told reporters that his officers were only "securing" the station because it was under attack.
Papua police spokesman Branch Chief Pudjo Sulistiyo said in 2015, "We have to defend ourselves when people threaten to kill us".
"It's a matter of life and death".
According to Human Rights Watch, five young protesters were killed and many more injured.
News of the deaths did not reach Jakarta until the following day.
Jokowi made an impassioned speech three weeks later in Jayapura, expressing his condolences to the families of the victims and promising to address historical abuses in Papua.
He said, "I want this case solved immediately so it won't happen again".
Security Minister Wiranto said in October 2016 that he had established a non-judicial mechanism for historical human rights violations.
But the excuses started almost immediately.
"Most of the violations happened a long time ago.
Some in the '90s, some in the early 2000s.
The point is that we are committed to resolving these violations, but there are processes that we have to go through".
Speaking to TIME on June 5, Wiranto backtracked, saying he had no plans to set up a complaints mechanism in Papua.
Instead, he said, "It'll all be settled by the law".
Wiranto said 11 cases of human rights violations in Papua, including the Paniai incident, had already been resolved, with the UN accusing East Timor of "crimes against humanity" linked to more than 1,000 deaths during the country's bloody 1999 independence vote.
The families of Paniai's victims greeted such claims with bitter skepticism.
"In the past three years, I have been interviewed four times, but there has been no progress", says Yohanes.
"I'm tired now".
Years later, he says he still lives in fear.
He says, "I'm scared".
"I'm afraid of being arrested by the military, I'm afraid of being shot".
His brother, Yacobus, echoes the view that people in Paniai were afraid to discuss the incident.
He says he was beaten by soldiers after he helped bury four of the victims.
"After I buried the bodies, the soldier came looking for me".
The attacks have not stopped yet.
On Tuesday, Indonesian police fired on villagers in Paniai's neighboring Deiyai regency.
One person was killed and 17 others, including children, were injured when villagers clashed with the manager of a construction company who refused to help take an unconscious man to the hospital.
Twenty-four-year-old Ravianus Douw drowned in a nearby lake while fishing and died en route to the hospital.
Angry villagers protested in front of the company's construction office.
Police said villagers threw stones at officers, who responded with warning shots.
But locals say the mobile brigade (Indonesian paramilitary police) opened fire on the crowd and killed one person.
Dominggu Badii, 29, who lives near the hospital and witnessed the wounded being brought in, told TIME, "We were very panicked, we were afraid of retaliation".
"I've been hiding in my house for two days".
Deiyai's parliament has called for the officers involved to be held accountable and for the mobile police brigade to be withdrawn from the area.
Paniai has always been a problematic area for the Indonesian government.
The lack of meaningful development is fueling discontent among the Mee, Moni, Dani and Damal tribal peoples who live scattered across Papua's verdant mountainous heartland.
Many joined the Free Papua Movement (OPM), a rebel army that claimed to protect the rights of Papuans by carrying out random attacks and kidnapping raids on Indonesian soldiers.
Some of the top OPM leaders, including Tadius Yogi and Daniel Yudas Kogoya, are from Paniai.
In response, thousands of people in Paniai have been arrested and arbitrarily detained by the military in recent years under the guise of "protecting national sovereignty".
Some are never seen again.
Among Papuans, Paniai is known as "a tragic and forgotten place".
Poverty feeds on discontent.
The little rice on sale in Enarotali is too expensive for the locals to buy.
Bread is out of reach.
People here grow everything they eat: mainly nuts, but also some fruits and leafy vegetables.
Farming is the work of women who can maintain four or five fields of sweet potatoes.
They usually save most of the harvest for the family and sell the rest at the local market.
10 notes are only 10,000 Indonesian rupiah (75 cents).
Over time, economic inequalities grew between the indigenous Papuans and the new immigrants who arrived in greater numbers since the opening of new air routes to Nabire Airport.
Jobs that are already scarce often go to better-educated and wealthier immigrants.
Papuans rarely have the capital or skills to run their own businesses competitively.
"Young people are not interested in staying in the village because there is no work or money", says John Gobai, chairman of the Panai tribal council.
Isolation keeps the world's eyes off Papua.
In addition, reporting restrictions for international media remain tight.
Earlier this year, French journalists Franck Escudie and Basille Longchamp were deported from Papua for "lack of coordination with relevant institutions", despite being rarely given permission to film.
According to Phelim Kine, deputy Asia director of Human Rights Watch, Jokowi's campaign promises to lift restrictions on reporting and improve transparency have not been fulfilled.
In a statement, he said: "There are new dangers for foreign journalists trying to cover Indonesia's restive easternmost provinces of Papua and West Papua: visa denial and blacklisting".
The lack of press censorship means that international pressure on the Indonesian government is mostly limited to Papua's immediate neighbours.
In March, six Pacific nations (Tonga, Nauru, Palau, Tuvalu, the Marshall Islands, and the Solomon Islands) urged the U.N. Human Rights Council to investigate "various and widespread violations" in Papua, including the Panaia attacks.
The same countries that have historically supported the OPM.
Indonesian Foreign Ministry spokesman Arrmanatha Nasir dismissed the group's claims, telling reporters in Jakarta, "Indonesia still has a democratic system and free media, so it is difficult to cover up evidence in human rights cases".
The locals want more foreign government involvement.
When an official delegation from the Netherlands, led by the country's human rights envoy Kees Van Baar, visited Jayapura on May 4, local people broke their silence with cries of "We want freedom", according to a source who attended the meeting and asked not to be named.
Indonesia has another presidential election in 2019, but Papuans say they are unlikely to vote for Jokowi again.
"Jokowi is a person with good intentions, but he is surrounded by people involved in the Paniai attack", says Gobai, the head of the tribal council.
Jokowi wants the people of Paniai to know that besides living under the imminent threat of the tyrannical military, they are also wallowing in poverty with meager education and health services.
Gobai says that the Paniai people, like other Papuans, see their vote as a "debt" to Jokowi to pay back.
"They don't need money, they just want justice".
Despite threats and intimidation, the families of the victims of the Paniai attack carried out a final symbolic act of defiance: burying the body of a victim in a field directly opposite the police and military station.
Knowing that justice may never be served, they will at least ensure that those responsible are not forgotten.
"A member of our family was killed", says Yacobus, bowing his head.
"What else can we do?"
Fire engulfs Dubai's 'Torch' skyscraper for the second time
A fire engulfed the world's tallest residential towers in Dubai on Friday, forcing hundreds of residents to flee the 337-meter-tall, 79-story structure.
This is the second major fire in two years to rapidly spread to the towering structure known as the Torch.
The building was evacuated, no injuries were reported, and no explanation was given as to the cause of the massive fire.
"We were sleeping and we woke up to the fire alarm, people screaming.
We ran down the stairs and it took us about 10 minutes to get down from the 50th floor", a resident who gave his name as George told Reuters.
Dubai's civil defence authorities said firefighters extinguished the massive blaze around 4am local time (00:00 GMT) and were cooling the building.
The government has announced that they are trying to provide shelter for those affected.
The incident may reopen questions about the safety of materials used in the exterior of tall buildings around the world.
Torch management's investigation after the 2015 fire found that most of the damage was to the cladding, the exterior panels used for decoration and insulation.
In the United Kingdom, police said they believed the insulation and cladding panel system on London's Grenfell Tower, where 80 people died, may have contributed to the rapid spread of the fire there in June.
'Social assistance' good news for more than 4,000 chronically ill patients
According to the Ministry of Family and Social Policies, 4 thousand 300 tuberculosis and SSPE patients will benefit from the social assistance program to be launched for poor citizens and their families struggling with chronic diseases in the first phase.
The Ministry, which plans to provide patients with a monthly support of two-thirds of the minimum wage through the assistance program, will also provide regular psychosocial support.
According to the information received, the details and application principles of the "New Social Assistance Program for Families Struggling with Chronic Diseases", which began its work some time ago by the instruction of the Minister of Family and Social Policies Fatma Betül Sayan Kaya, became known.
The social assistance program, which was launched in cooperation with the Ministry of Health to support citizens struggling with chronic diseases and experiencing economic and psychological difficulties, is the first of its kind in the world.
The Ministry, which has completed all the necessary preparations for the launch of the program, will provide not only cash but also regular psychosocial support to families through the social assistance program.
Thus, it is aimed that poor citizens with chronic diseases and their families who continue their treatment processes at home are not left alone both financially and spiritually.
According to studies, in the first phase, poor citizens struggling with tuberculosis disease and subacute sclerosing panencephalitis (SSPE), a brain disease caused by the measles virus, will be provided regular psychosocial and cash support under the new social assistance program.
In the later stages of the program, other poor citizens struggling with rare and risky diseases will be covered by the program.
In addition to the support, which is planned to be paid at a rate of more than two-thirds of the minimum wage, an additional payment will also be made to tuberculosis patients who are unable to afford medical self-care, are bedridden or whose home living conditions need to be improved.
In order to qualify for support, the household's monthly income per person must be less than two thirds of the net monthly minimum wage.
In addition, citizens who are SSPE patients must have a health board report organized according to the procedures and principles specified in the "Regulation on the Measure of Independence, Classification and Health Board Reports to be Given to the Disabled".
Survey reveals that more than 1 in 5 U.S. airline passengers carries banned items
According to a survey of airline passengers, more than 20 percent had knowingly or unknowingly smuggled prohibited items through U.S. Transportation Security Administration checkpoints, including at least 6 percent who had unknowingly carried prohibited knives or other sharp objects.
Less than 1 percent claimed that they later realized that they had accidentally traveled with firearms, ammunition, or explosives.
A study of more than 1,000 people conducted by Stratos Jet Charters, a jet charter service, also found that younger passengers were more likely to break the rules.
Of the participants who admitted to knowingly trying to fly something prohibited by the TSA, 19.7 percent were millennials, while less than 15 percent were members of generation X.
The most common items intentionally taken from TSA agents are food and liquids.
More than 3 percent admitted knowingly bringing sharp objects through security, while 2.2 percent of female respondents and 3.7 percent of male respondents also admitted knowingly bringing illicit drugs on board.
The firm said it was conducting a nationwide survey of passengers to find out how many airport security personnel had inadvertently brought in contraband and how many had done so knowingly.
It's no surprise that the people most likely to knowingly or unknowingly smuggle contraband through security are the ones who fly the most.
However, as the firm points out, TSA regulations are a bit convoluted and confusing.
People often aren't sure what fluids or how much of them they can carry.
So it's no surprise that the largest amount of drugs seized by the TSA turned out to be illicit liquids.
For a while, people thought the TSA might be treating the books as contraband.
Liquids are allowed on domestic flights but not on international ones.
China welcomed the US statements
At a press conference in Beijing, Chinese Foreign Minister Wang Yi said that Tillerson's statements about the Pyongyang government were important: "Regime change, regime collapse, rapid reunification of the peninsula, and we are not looking for excuses to send our troops north of the 38th parallel".
Chinese Foreign Minister Wang Yi said Tillerson reiterated the Washington administration's principles on the North Korea issue and hoped the US would implement these principles effectively and in a policy focused on concrete results.
Noting that the security of the Korean peninsula is their priority, Wang said that they expect the parties to find a middle way to resolve their concerns through equal dialogue, stressing that Beijing has long insisted on the denuclearization of the peninsula, the protection of peace and stability, and the resolution of problems through dialogue and negotiation.
Pruitt, the head of the EPA, has given up on delaying Obama-era emissions-reduction laws.
A day after being sued by 15 states, Environmental Protection Agency chairman Scott Pruitt reversed an earlier decision to delay the implementation of Obama-era laws that reduced emissions of air pollutants that cause smog.
Pruitt represented change in that his organization was more responsive to the needs of state environmental regulators than past administrations.
He made no mention of a legal challenge to his former position in a federal appeals court.
What's at stake is that states start meeting the October 1 deadline for 2015 standards for ground-level ozone.
Pruitt announced in June that he would delay compliance for a year to give his organization more time to work on the plan and to avoid "interfering with local decisions or impeding economic growth".
Pruitt, who was Oklahoma's state attorney general before being appointed by President Donald Trump, had long served as a reliable ally against stricter environmental regulations.
Since arriving in Washington, Pruitt has repeatedly moved to block or delay regulations opposed by the chemical and fossil fuel industries.
Wednesday's abrupt change is the latest legal defeat for Pruitt's agenda to roll back regulation.
Last month, a federal appeals court in Washington ruled that the EPA administrator overstepped his authority when he tried to delay an Obama administration law requiring oil and gas companies to monitor and reduce methane leaks.
In a statement released Wednesday evening, Pruitt argued that the rollback of the ozone standards only strengthened the EPA's commitment to work with states to meet the new standards in a timely manner and through complex processes.
Pruitt, who sued the EPA more than a dozen times in his previous job, said, "Under previous administrations, the EPA often failed to meet deadlines for rulings, waited to be sued by activist groups and others, and agreed to settle the dispute to set timelines for a decision".
"We don't believe in regulation through litigation and we take deadlines seriously.
We also take seriously the law and the authority it gives us".
Still, the EPA statement noted that Pruitt could use his "delay power and all other legally available authority" one more time at some point to ensure that regulations are "supported by sound policies and the best available information".
Republicans in Congress are pushing for a broader rewrite of the ozone laws.
A parliamentary bill approved last month seeks to delay implementation of the 2015 laws by at least eight years.
The measure has not yet been brought to the Senate for a vote.
New York Attorney General Eric Schneiderman, who is leading a coalition of states suing the EPA this week, said the group intends to keep up the legal pressure.
Schneiderman said, "The EPA's reversal following our lawsuits is a significant victory for the health and safety of 6.7 million New Yorkers and the more than 115 million Americans directly affected by the dirty smoke pouring into their communities".
New York was joined in the lawsuit by California, Connecticut, Delaware, Illinois, Iowa, Maine, Massachusetts, Minnesota, New Mexico, Oregon, Pennsylvania, Rhode Island, Vermont and Washington and the District of Columbia.
Ground-level ozone is produced when general pollutants are released into the atmosphere by automobiles, power plants, oil refineries, chemical plants, and other sources that respond to sunlight.
The resulting foul smoke can cause severe respiratory problems in susceptible people and contributes to thousands of premature deaths each year.
Public health advocates and environmentalists applauded Pruitt's surprise reversal.
Lori Ann Burd of the Center for Biological Diversity said: "It's disturbing that it took so much pressure to get this common-sense step from the person responsible for protecting the air we breathe".
"We must continue to fight the Trump administration's ideological struggle to curry favor with polluters and special interests".
Inflation in single digits
Turkey, which recorded the biggest increase in exports in 6 years in July, reduced unemployment from 13 percent in January to 10.5 percent in April and raised the economic confidence index to a 3.5 year high, reduced inflation to a single digit.
According to the data announced yesterday by the Turkish Statistical Institute (TÜİK), the Consumer Price Index (TÜFE) rose by 0.15 percent in July, while the annual inflation fell to 9.79 percent for the first time since January.
As for the main spending groups, in July, the highest increase on a monthly basis was seen in the restaurant and hotel group with 1.75%, while the group with the largest decrease was clothing and footwear with 3.51%.
On an annual basis, the highest increase was in the transportation group with 15.24 percent.
Business Investment Economist Muammer Kömürcüoğlu, who pointed out that inflation decreased to a single digit in July, parallel to expectations, said, "The moderate course of inflation is influenced by the decline in food and clothing prices".
But contrary to the headline, the core indicators are up from the previous month.
"We do not expect a relaxation of the central bank's tough stance", he said.
Despite the decline in headline inflation, core inflation indicators increased.
The B index of the special comprehensive TÜFE indicators closely monitored by the Central Bank rose from 9.07 percent to 9.46 percent in July, while the C index rose from 9.20 percent to 9.60 percent.
Kapital FX Research Assistant Director Enver Erkan stated that inflation may close the year at 9.3 percent, "Inflation may fluctuate until December and fall to one household in December".
"The Central Bank may have an opportunity as early as the first months of 2018", he explained.
Deputy Prime Minister Mehmet Şimşek: Inflation will end the year in single digits.
The Fed's tightening will continue until inflation falls below 7 percent.
We'll finalize the reforms at the next Food Committee.
Economy Minister Nihat Zeybekci: We are happy that inflation has dropped to single digits, but it needs to become permanent.
In order to combat inflation, it is necessary to increase supply as well as reduce food price volatility.
Development Minister Lütfi Elvan: In the coming months, annual inflation may show some upward trend due to the base effect, but from the first months of 2018, the decline in inflation will become apparent.
We expect annual inflation to fall further.
I wish Fenerbahce success in their next matches.
