The group wants to fight against the regime of Bashar al-Assad as well as Daesh.
According to leaked phone records, Trump pressured Mexico to pay for his border wall.
Notes of telephone conversations between U.S. President Donald Trump and the leaders of Mexico and Australia were leaked by the Washington Post.
In a January 27 phone call with Mexican President Enrique Pena Nieto, Trump pressed him not to say publicly that he would not pay for the proposed border wall.
The president of the United States scolded the president of Mexico for publicly throwing a ball against the wall and reportedly said, "You can't tell the press that".
Trump launched his presidential campaign on building a wall along the southern border of the United States, promising Mexico he would pay for the project.
Notes have also been released of his first meeting with Australian Prime Minister Malcolm Turnbull, which sparked a heated dialogue.
Mr. Trump told Mr. Turnbull that the U.S. agreement to take refugees to Australia was a "farce", "rotten" and "stupid", and that the Obama administration's deal would make itself look "foolish" after he proposed a ban on refugee resettlement in the U.S.
Mr. Trump ended his speech by telling Mr. Turnbull, "That was the most unpleasant speech I've had all day".
Relatives of the patient broke the doctor's nose.
Doctors and employees of Turkey's Higher Specialized Education and Research Hospital left work briefly yesterday morning in response to the beating of a doctor colleague by the patient's relatives.
A large crowd gathered in front of the hospital's main entrance, carrying placards that read "No to violence in health".
Prof. Dr. Feyza Ayşenur Paç, Head of the Hospital's Pediatric Cardiology Clinic, said, "The slogan 'No to violence in health' seems to me to be insufficient and even a party slogan".
Violence has no place in healthcare.
"If it goes on like this, this nation will soon find itself without a health group to serve it".
The health workers' action was supported by Dr. Kamil Turkmen, Ankara Provincial Health Director, Prof. Dr. Öner Odabaş, General Secretary of Ankara First District Public Hospitals, Prof. Dr. Mustafa Paç, Chief Physician of the Turkish Higher Specialized Education and Research Hospital, and patients' relatives in the hospital garden.
Paç condemned the incident and said:
Unfortunately, violence against healthcare workers is on the rise.
An example of this occurred last night when our cardiovascular surgeon was beaten by a patient's relative.
Although our state, our ministry and our governorate are taking all possible measures to end these incidents as soon as possible, we demand that our people's sensitivity in this matter also increase.
I condemn the events of yesterday on behalf of my hospital and my medical staff.
Odabaş pointed out that society needs to be aware of violence in health, "Unfortunately, this has become a professional complication that we experience from time to time".
"We will also take our own precautions, but the most important thing is that our nation has its own health worker", he said.
Turkmen also stated that the judicial process regarding the incident has begun, "Our laws regarding violence in health have been effective enough".
It's practiced at all levels of government.
Police are working on it now.
In the past, they've always sat vacant, but now it's a straightforward public trial, and the state appoints an attorney, prosecutes the case.
"There are also examples of severe punishment for this", he said.
After the explanations, the workers went back to work.
The incident allegedly occurred around 5:45 p.m. the day before.
Relatives of the patient who died in intensive care attacked Dr. Hamdi Mehmet Özbek, who worked in the Department of Cardiovascular Surgery.
Police were called to the hospital as Özbek was being escorted away by doctors and assistants.
While Özbek's nose was broken, the attackers were detained.
A doctor who witnessed the incident said:
When our friend went to inform the relatives of a patient who had died, the relatives blamed our friend and us and attacked our two friends.
Our friend's nose is broken, he's covered in blood.
Then we took our friend into the O.R. and hid him.
There was a security barrier between us for 15 or 20 minutes.
If the patient's family had breached that firewall, much worse things would have happened.
In Gaziantep, a heavy blow was dealt to Daesh: 102 sacks...
