Delayed perception of the realities of the country and the world can lead not only to ordinary people but also to countries being dragged into crises.
One of the reasons for the delayed perception of the world realities by the backward East, which we describe as "Orientalism", may be that the reflection of these realities on the geographies of the East is blocked by certain focuses or announced in a surreal way.
Don Quixote and Oblomov The delayed or absent perception of reality and change has also been the subject of the literary world.
Cervantes' "Don Quixote" is about a madman who still thinks he's a knight in a time when the bourgeoisie is beginning to form.
Or Goncharov's "Oblomov" is the legacy of a lazy man who thought that when he ignored reality, everything could go on as before.
China, for example, was open to the world and dominated the seas until the end of the 15th century, when a conservative dynasty took over.
