Moore's Ford massacre: Activists revive racist lynching to call for justice
A 1948 Ford Mercury plowed through a crowd of spectators in rural Monroe, Georgia, and rattled toward the little Ford Bridge in Moore.
Before the car, which had four black passengers and a white driver, reached the bridge, a group of armed white men stepped forward to block its path.
The gang leader, a middle-aged man in a pinstriped suit, took a long drag on his cigar and peered through the windshield.
Inside, the occupants trembled in fear.
"We want that shit, Roger!" he barked.
"Get him out of the car!"
Screams pierced the darkness as a young black man was dragged from the front passenger seat.
Fortunately, this horrific scene of June 22nd is only a reenactment.
But when a noose was thrown around "Roger's" neck, almost everyone in the audience breathed quite realistically.
Since 2005, human rights advocates have returned to Ford's Bridge in Moore to re-enact the 1946 lynching of two black couples (Roger and Dorothy Malcom and George and Mae Murray Dorsey) by the Ku Klux Klan.
So far, no one has been charged in connection with the murders.
Tyrone Brooks, who helped organize the revival, said: "It's unbelievable that in all these years not one person has been arrested, even though we see them in our communities, even though we know who they are".
"It's a stain on history but a burden on our souls".
Brooks is a 71-year-old former congressman from Georgia and a lifelong civil rights advocate.
For him, this reenactment is a dramatic call to action and an annual reminder to the Monroe community that an injustice is never righted.
He said, "We want prosecution, we want results, we want healing, we want reconciliation, but we have to get justice first".
"We cannot have healing and reconciliation until we have justice".
The coroner places a sheet over the body of one of the victims of the Ford lynching in Moore on July 27, 1946.
According to FBI files obtained by NBC News, more than 50 men from Monroe and surrounding areas were suspected in the lynching.
But not one of them was ever investigated.
Although the suspects have remained at large for decades, human rights advocates say the twin motivations of lynchings have always been well known throughout the town: politics and sex.
A high court ruling in April 1946 had allowed Georgia's black citizens to vote for the first time in a primary election later that summer.
According to the FBI, around the same time as the election, black business associate Roger Malcom stabbed a white landowner, Barnett Hester, during a fight, apparently over a woman.
Brooks stated that the rumor in town was that Hester was sleeping with Dorothy, Malcolm's wife, and that the baby she was carrying was not her husband's.
According to the FBI, on July 25, 1946, Loy Harrison, a prominent white landowner, paid $600 to get Malcolm out of jail.
Dorothy and her cousins went to jail with Mae Murray and George Dorsey.
But as they drove away from the prison, they came to the Ford Bridge in Moore and a lynch mob surrounded the car.
An FBI report concludes, "It appears that Harrison arranged and ordered the murders".
"It is also clear that there was collusion between state and local law enforcement who not only participated in the murder but destroyed evidence and concealed the identities of witnesses".
Brooks was more succinct.
He said, "It was a voting rights massacre".
"They were all killed to send a message to black people in this community: 'This is what will happen to you if you register and vote.'"
For nearly a decade, Cassandra Greene has directed the annual reenactment of the Ford Bridge lynchings in Moore.
Her performance is nuanced, compelling, and rooted in a deep kind of racism that many believe no longer exists in America.
It's hard to watch, and even harder to look away, but Greene says that's the point.
He said, "We don't want to talk about lynching because it brings out the ugliness in all of us".
"But I can't have a relationship with you if you don't listen to me or what's going on with me".
Rehearsals for this year's production began in June, and on the first day about 30 actors (a dozen white and the rest black) crowded into a room and listened as Greene eagerly outlined the well-rehearsed play.
Wade Marbaugh serves as Greene's co-director.
For years, he's played President Klansman, but he says it's never been easy.
Marbaugh said, "I feel dirty because this isn't me".
"But I think it's important to keep that history alive because we don't want to go back to that time".
Across the room, the actors playing Roger Malcolm and Barnett Hester, Darrius Bradshaw and Nick Rascona, were rehearsing their lines.
The play begins with Malcolm yelling at and pushing Hester, who is furious that he slept with his wife Dorothy.
"I said get the fuck off my property!"
He's responding to the Rascona.
There's a thump.
And then everyone (at least the black actors) burst out laughing.
Greene gets the most laughs.
Rascona said, "What?"
He was nervous, he was surprised.
Was I too harsh?
"No", said Greene with a chuckle.
"I just don't think white people said dick back then".
One of the black players said, "Yes", and jokingly threw rocks.
"You have to press the R".
So the energy in the room changes and a kind of intimacy replaces the uneasiness.
Everyone is dedicated to getting this right, not only for the sake of the game but also for the memory of the four people who were killed.
The scene starts again.
This time Rascona says the N-word, sharp and emphatic.
Absolutely no one is laughing.
The reanimation ends violently and quickly.
There's screaming and gunfire and then silence.
A woman dressed in black funeral attire stands over the bodies of the actors and recites Billie Holiday's mournful eulogy "Strange Fruit".
His voice breaks at every other word.
A hundred yards back, an average crowd of four dozen is wiping sweat and tears from their eyes.
The audience is almost evenly split between black and white.
A couple flew in from Ithaca, New York, to see the performance, most of them from up the road.
They all endured the oppressive humidity of Georgia for nearly eight hours as Brooks took them on a pilgrimage to the graves of the Malcolms and the Dorseys.
Up to this point, the murders had remained anecdotal, but now standing in the same spot as the lynching means the air feels cursed.
As the final notes of the song fade, Greene invites the crowd to come closer and examine the bodies.
The children squat on their hands, grasping the fake blood and motionless bodies and whispering to each other.
"They're not really dead", murmurs a little boy, as if reminding himself.
A few minutes later, Greene thanks the crowd and it's over.
The actors throw the noose and wipe away their tears.
Bradshaw hugs Marbaugh in the suit who plays the Klansman president.
Nick Rascona hugs two of his co-stars and tears roll down his cheeks as the emotional toll of the performance finally catches up with him.
One of the women whispers, "It's okay".
"We know that's not what's in your heart.
You did it for a reason".
Then the audience sits down to dinner with the actors.
At a table, a white couple from Atlanta and a black couple have a passionate conversation about revitalization.
Denise Duplinski struggles to find the words to describe how the performance made her feel.
He said, "To hear these horrible, awful words and these actions... coming from people who look like you, and they're doing it because they look like you".
"What that does to me is make me think that lynchings are still going on", he added, "and they're just called police shootings now".
Across the room, Tyrone Brooks is the center of attention as he eats dinner at his desk and recounts his civil rights memories.
He said he's already planning next year's performance.
He said: "The reenactment is inspiring in a way because it describes what we endured, but it is also instructive".
"Like, if you don't learn from it, it could happen again.
Those who do not examine their past, those who do not know their past, are condemned to repeat it".
