Eight-month returns on the Istanbul stock exchange were 50 percent.
The BIST 100 index continued its upward trend that began in December 2016 in July and carried its rise to the 8th month in a row.
Thus, the index gained 45.3 percent in this period, while recording an increase of 8 consecutive months for the first time since July 2007.
The BIST 100 index, which has outperformed the world's major stock exchanges, including Germany, the US, the UK and Japan, with its performance since the beginning of the year, did not leave the lead in terms of returns in July.
The BIST 100 index, which ended July with a rise of 7.06 percent, was followed by the Dow Jones index in the United States with a rise of 2.54 percent and the FTSE 100 index in the United Kingdom with a rise of 0.81 percent.
The DAX index in Germany and the Nikkei index in Japan ended July with losses.
As of the January-July period, the BIST 100 index has outperformed both major world stock exchanges and emerging market stock indices.
This year, the BIST 100 gained 37.6 percent, the Dow Jones gained 10.76 percent, the DAX gained 5.55 percent, the Nikkei gained 4.55 percent, and the FTSE 100 gained 3.21 percent.
The MSCI EM index, an indicator of emerging market equities, returned 23 percent.
Looking at the historical course of the BIST 100 index, it has shown similar performances in the past.
The BIST 100 index, which last gained value for eight consecutive months between December 2006 and July 2007, recorded a 38.3 percent increase in this period.
In addition, the BIST 100 index had completed 8 consecutive months of gains between August 1996 and March 1997, and 9 consecutive months of gains between May 1997 and January 1998.
Meksa Yatırım Research Manager Eren Can Umut told Anadolu Agency that the BIST 100 index has continued to rise for 8 months and has exceeded 37 percent since the beginning of the year.
Umut pointed out that the MSCI emerging markets (EM) index recorded a 23 percent rise, stating that even if we look at these rates alone, there is a positive differentiation:
The flow of funds to developing countries has continued since the beginning of the year.
In particular, funds seeking higher returns prefer countries with higher interest rates.
This is already having a positive impact on domestic markets.
Of course, on a global scale, the appetite for risk is also quite high.
This makes stock indices, which have the status of risky assets, popular.
In the U.S., we see new record highs being tested almost every week as the S&P 500 index has risen nearly 11 percent since Christmas.
Umut stressed that the US Federal Reserve's (Fed) 3 percent hike forecast at the beginning of the year put markets under stress, but the Fed's verbal guidance policy eliminated the uncertainty quite well, noting that there is a market that is insensitive to the Fed's interest rate hike.
Umut stated that inflation in the US is not yet at the desired level, and the expectations that the Fed will not be hasty in raising interest rates and will avoid radical moves are also very influential in current pricing.
Not being able to cancel the healthcare reform known as "Obamacare" by US President Donald Trump has strengthened the perception that he will not be able to fulfill his promises of expansionary fiscal policies.
Umut pointed out that 2016 was a year of many negatives for Turkey's markets and said that the negative divergence and oversold BIST 100 index was in an effort to close the gap with its peers.
Noting that they did not see a strong recovery with the flow of domestically sourced news, Umut noted that the current outlook can be interpreted more as an increase in risk appetite abroad and a desire to close the gap between domestic markets and similar ones.
Umut stated that he technically tracked some profit selling in the BIST 100 index, which tested new records with levels of 108.600, noting:
Especially the 109,500-110,000 area is a critical threshold in the short term.
It's normal for profit-taking to occur as it approaches these levels.
In the short term, we think there needs to be a new local or global narrative for valuations above 110,000.
For now, a breakdown of the 107,500 support could trigger profit selling.
In this case, even though we're tracking the intermediate support at 107,000, I think we can see a loosening to the 106,000-105,500 area.
In particular, a break of the support at 105.500 could trigger a pullback to 104.300, which is Fibo 50% of the move from 100,000 to 108.600.
Stating that the decisions of both the Fed and the European Central Bank (ECB) will be in the focus of the global market, Umut said that the expectations for the Fed are already clear, but the possibility of the balance sheet reduction program triggering the strengthening in the US dollar may trigger the strengthening in the US dollar.
Umut noted that this could trigger short-term profit selling in developing country (DC) stock indexes, which are in the shadow of overbought conditions. "What is important is what the ECB will say".
