New results of Sweden's asylum age assessment test released
The latest results of a Swedish assessment of refugees undergoing a new method of medical age assessment concluded that more than 80 percent of those tested were over the age of 18, but not everyone trusts the accuracy of these tests.
Sweden's national Office of Forensic Medicine and Pharmacy (Rättsmedicinalverket) began testing earlier this year.
The tests were designed to make age assessment in the asylum process more accurate after criticism of the Swedish Migration Board's (Migrationsverket) failure to assess the correct age of some refugees who claimed to be underage.
To date, the Migration Board has sent 6,880 cases for testing, and the State Agency of Forensic Medicine and Pharmacy has now published the results of a total of 2,481 tests from the period from mid-March to 31 July 2017.
Eighty percent (2002 figure) were judged to be 18 or over, and in 25 cases the Bureau of Forensics and Drug Enforcement ruled the subject was "probably 18 and over".
In 432 cases, the conclusion was that the person was "probably under 18".
The tests were only performed in cases where the age of the person was in doubt.
According to Johan Göransson of the Department of Forensic Medicine, the results are consistent with previous months.
"We don't see a big difference in the statistics from previous months, the numbers are pretty consistent", he told The Local.
The high rate of convictions over the age of 18 does not necessarily mean that refugees are lying about their age.
In May, the department released the results of 581 tests and said that there were 442 cases "in which the persons examined were shown to be 18 years of age or older".
When the newspaper Svenska Dagbladet examined the results of 581 reported cases, it found that 243 cases clearly stated that they had turned 18 that year.
The medical method of age assessment, which involves taking X-rays of the 20-year-old's teeth and MRI scans of his knee joints, then sending them to dentists and radiologists for analysis, has been criticized in some circles.
One skeptic is Claude Marcus, an endocrinologist at the Karolinska Institute, who has also studied the biological maturity of people who enter puberty earlier or later than normal.
"I have reasons to think about it, and I think that's not the kind of measurement that should be used.
That's a very dubious way to judge biological age.
If we can't say for sure, we shouldn't pretend".
However, Göransson, of the Medical Examiner's Office, defended the accuracy of the tests: "In general, you can say that the risk of a child being mistaken for an adult is small.
The greatest risk is just before age 18, when the risk is about 10 percent".
