How will football's financial rules affect Neymar's move to Paris?
Rules aimed at preventing unlimited spending by European football clubs will not prevent Neymar's world-record transfer from Barcelona, Spain to Paris-Saint Germain, France.
From UEFA, the governing body that oversees the European game, with the power to ban teams from the prestigious Champions League tournament, to Paris Saint-Germain, anything can happen.
Financial Fair Play rules introduced by UEFA in 2011 mean that PSG will eventually have to show that they financed Neymar's transfer without suffering huge losses.
Barcelona was paid 222 million euros ($262 million) just to buy the Brazilian out of his contract, and Neymar will command a salary in the tens of millions of dollars a year.
Here are some of the financial aspects of Neymar's move to France:
Given that the team's money comes from an energy-rich Qatari family, PSG can certainly afford to sign Neymar and add him to the galaxy of other stars.
Clubs are allowed to spend large sums of money on players, but they must balance this with legitimate sources of income, provided they have a direct link to football-related business.
FFP was conceived by Michel Platini after his election as UEFA president in 2007.
The former French player believed that clubs that incurred large debts in pursuit of success were effectively cheating and were at risk of bankruptcy if banks or owners withdrew their support.
In 2011, FFP began to monitor clubs' losses rather than concentrate on their debts.
The change meant that the model first used by Roman Abramovich at Chelsea in 2003 (buy a club with potential, spend heavily to improve the team and build a global brand) became a more difficult endeavour.
During the 3-year FFP evaluation period, which runs until 2018, clubs can incur losses of 30 million euros.
Despite Platini's dishonorable dismissal from the presidency in 2015, his successor at UEFA, Aleksander Ceferin, is still determined to discourage excessive spending.
Andrea Traverso, who oversees FFP at UEFA, told the Associated Press last week: "FFP is definitely not dead and we will definitely strengthen the rules moving forward".
Although PSG will pay Neymar's buyout clause in one lump sum, it can spread the amount over the duration of the contract for accounting reasons.
Neymar signed a 5-year contract, so the transfer fee can be shown in the annual accounts for the next 5 years as a cost of 44.4 million euros.
The first wave of FFP sanctions in 2014 saw the heaviest sanctions imposed on Manchester City, owned by PSG and Abu Dhabi.
PSG was fined 60 million euros ($82 million at the time), which was later reduced to 20 million euros, and ordered to limit its Champions League squad to 21 players instead of the normal 25 for the 2014-2015 season.
UEFA is wary of clubs that may try to cheat financial regulators by inflating their income through companies linked to the club's owners.
Although a Qatari company can sponsor PSG, if the value of the sponsorship is considered to exceed standard market values, UEFA will not allow it to count as legitimate income.
This was the case in 2014, when UEFA ruled that the Qatar Tourism Authority's sponsorship of PSG was inflated.
It has been reported that part of Neymar's earnings from PSG could come through payments from Qatar's 2022 World Cup organising committee.
But PSG and Qatar have denied that Neymar will be an ambassador for the 2022 World Cup, and such a move could easily be uncovered by UEFA regulators.
The sanctions imposed on PSG in the past mean that UEFA will be even more vigilant against attempts to circumvent the rules.
UEFA is not in preventive talks with PSG over Neymar's transfer, sources familiar with the matter said on Tuesday.
They spoke to The Associated Press on condition of anonymity because they were not authorized to discuss PSG's situation.
The latest published accounts show that PSG made a profit of over €10 million on a turnover of €542.4 million in 2015-16.
The accounts for the last financial year have not yet been published.
PSG expects Neymar's arrival to contribute to sponsorship deals, gifts and shirt sales.
The club expects a turnover increase of at least 30% after the signing.
Clearly upset by the departure of one of football's greatest players, the Spanish league tried to block Neymar's departure, claiming that PSG had violated FFP.
"This is an open case of 'financial doping' with the club and the state", La Liga president Javier Tebas told Spanish newspaper AS, referring to Qatar's definitive ownership of PSG.
Arsenal manager Arsene Wenger, whose own club is owned by an American sports giant, shares his concerns about La Liga being financed by a state.
"It's a consequence of ownership and it's completely changed the whole landscape of football in the last 15 years", Wenger said on Thursday.
"Once a country has a club, anything is possible.
It's very difficult to respect Financial Fair Play because for a country to have such a big player representing a country can lead to having different methods or different interests.
