NHS to prescribe controversial HIV drug to 10,000 people
Following a High Court battle over NHS funding for the drug, patients will be able to access 'transformative' HIV prevention treatment from September.
NHS England has announced that pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP), a pill taken before sex that has been shown to reduce the risk of infection by around 86 percent in high-risk individuals, will be provided by health services to around 10,000 people through a 3-year pilot trial.
The High Court decision last year agreed to fund the trial after the Court of Appeal upheld it, saying the NHS had the power to pay for PrEP despite claims that local authorities were funding it.
The move, announced on Thursday, was welcomed as a 'new and serious intervention' by NHS England chief executive Simon Stevens, while the National Aids Trust (NAT) described it as a 'turning point'.
Sexual health clinics in London, Brighton, Manchester, Liverpool and Sheffield will be the first clinics to enroll the public, with more clinics joining in October and being fully implemented across England by April 2018.
Pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) is a range of HIV medications that reduce the risk of contracting HIV before sex.
The trials showed that PrEP significantly reduced HIV transmission among those at risk of infection.
Taking PrEP before sex means that a person has enough of the medication in their body to prevent HIV infection from taking hold.
These medications can be taken every day or up to two hours before sex.
Eligible for treatment are gay or bisexual men, transgender people, and those with HIV-positive partners who cannot be successfully treated.
Clinics will identify eligible men, women, transgender individuals, and individuals whose partners are not known to be controlling their HIV status with antiretroviral therapy.
People living in the UK and registered with a GP will also be able to register for potential participation at participating local sexual health clinics.
The programme will cost £10 million and NHS England signed an agreement this week to provide the drugs through an international tender.
The trial was designed to evaluate the full potential of PrEP by gathering clinical evidence on how PrEP is targeted, administered and delivered at scale.
Mr. Stevens said: 'This new and serious intervention will contribute to the widespread and increasingly successful efforts to prevent HIV.
This is another milestone in three decades of progress toward conquering one of mankind's major health problems".
Deborah Gold, president of the National Aids Trust (NAT), said: 'This is a turning point in the fight against HIV.
If properly targeted at those who need it and those at risk, PrEP has the potential to transform the HIV epidemic in the UK.
Starting in September, people who are at high risk of HIV, through this NHS-funded trial in the UK, will have access to a new and powerful tool that is truly personally controlled and non-negotiable with a partner, which will lead to many lives being improved.
We warmly welcome this announcement.'
Ian Green, chairman of the Terrence Higgins Trust, said: 'The priority now must be to rapidly roll out testing across the country and ensure that no one at risk of HIV is left behind.
Now that the experimental PrEP drug is available, we are on track to protect more than 10,000 people at risk of HIV".
Shadow public health minister Sharon Hodgson said: 'We welcome the fact that the PrEP trial has started and has been delayed by months of delays and then government resistance.
The evidence shows how transformative this drug can be as part of our approach to preventing HIV and ending the transmission of this life-changing infection.
The trial will bring us one step closer to fully understanding the benefits of PrEP.
Now it's important that this trial be rolled out across the country as quickly as possible to protect people exposed to HIV and bring us one step closer to ending the spread of HIV in the community.
