Trump's new personal pen plans to restrict the president's media diet.
Others have tried and failed.
Maybe John F. Kelly really can do it.
If he does, he'll be the first.
Politico reports that the new White House chief of staff will restrict the flow of information (including news media reports) to President Trump in hopes of keeping his boss more stable.
Here's a little bit from reporter Josh Dawsey:
"When the White House's new chief of staff, John F. Kelly, met with senior staff on his first day in office, he outlined a fundamental problem President Donald Trump plans to solve with the White House: bad information getting into the president's hands.
Kelly told staff that information should flow through him, whether on paper or in briefings, because the president would be able to make better decisions when given good information.
Kelly's diagnosis makes a lot of sense, but others have tried and failed to moderate Trump by controlling his media diet.
President Trump's relationship with television goes back decades, and now that he's in the White House, his TV viewing habits are still good.
Sam Nunberg, a former campaign adviser, told Politico in February, "If candidate Trump is sorry he didn't get a fair shake in the media, it was productivity-enhancing to show him he got a fair shake in persuadable media organizations".
Tara Palmeri of Politico wrote at the time, "According to six campaign officials, the key to keeping Trump's Twitter habit in check was to ensure his personal media consumption included a steady stream of praise".
Okay, I got it.
But the idea that Trump's Twitter habit is "under control" at any given time is ridiculous.
Maybe these campaign officials know something the rest of us don't, like Trump's tweets would be far more inflammatory without their intervention.
We'll probably never know about the tweets Trump didn't send.
If his people were able to get him out of harm's way even a few times, then it was worth it.
But no one could stop Trump from constantly creating controversy.
Part of the problem was that the White House was made up of competing factions, people who were always trying to advance their own agenda with the materials they presented to Trump (which could be reliable or unreliable) and promoting their own worldviews.
Politico reported in May that throughout this whole story, advisers strategically tended to feed the president dubious information.
One example, detailed by reporter Shane Goldmacher, was this:
"Current and former Trump officials say Trump has reacted furiously to negative clippings from the press, especially leaks that have had a chilling effect, and is preoccupied with finding out where they originated.
That's what happened in late February when someone maliciously gave the president a printed copy of an article from internet provocateur Charles C. Johnson's GotNews.com that accused special assistant Katie Walsh of being the "source behind a series of leaks" in the White House.
It didn't matter that Johnson had been permanently banned from Twitter for harassment, or that he offered no concrete evidence, or that he had made false accusations in the past and then retracted them.
Trump read the article and started asking the staff questions about Walsh".
Goldmacher added that then-special pen Reince Priebus and White House staff secretary Rob Porter "tried to put in place a system that managed and documented the paperwork Trump received".
What was the result?
Kelly's trying to do the same thing three months later.
He may emerge as a more effective executive than Priebus, but Trump is still his own man and his aides are still vying for influence.
These immutable factors will make Kelly's task very difficult.
