Don't jump to conclusions
Prof. Dr. Yusuf Şükrü Çağlar, President of the Turkish Neurosurgery Association, warned against jumping into shallow places of more than 2 meters, where the depth is not certain.
Every year, thousands of people risk paralysis from neck fractures and spinal cord injuries from diving into shallow water.
Neck fractures most commonly occur at the fifth or sixth vertebra.
Fractures at this level are characterized by involvement of the nerves that supply the respiratory muscles as well as the muscles of the arms and legs.
Prof. Dr. Çağlar said, "In this type of accident, the cervical spine, which is our most valuable organ, is severed or compressed by the broken spine due to the fracture".
He said, "In the case of spinal cord injuries, incorrect first aid not only increases the damage to the accident victims, it can also lead to death".
Scuba diving is the fourth leading cause of spinal cord injury.
The average age of the wounded is between 20 and 29, and most of them are men.
Prof. Dr. Çağlar, "You shouldn't jump into the unknown".
He said, "No matter how well you dive, you can still get hurt".
Prof. Dr. Çağlar also reminded:
Paralysis of the arms and legs can occur to varying degrees, depending on the level of the spinal cord where the injury occurred.
You may know how to swim, but water can be deceptive.
What seems deep to you may be shallow.
In the United States and Australia, coastal warning signs have reduced the number of people jumping into shallow waters by 70 percent.
Prof. Dr. Çağlar said, "In Turkey, although 28 provinces have a coastline, unfortunately, there is not a single warning sign outside Istanbul".
"Before every summer, the health directorate of every province, schools and social awareness projects should have information lights or information boards on beaches and pools", he said.
TÜRK Neurosurgery Association Spinal and Peripheral Neurosurgery Group Chairman Prof. Dr. Kadir Kotil suggested the following in case of injury:
The first thing to do is call 911.
The neck should be held as steady as possible, not moved, fixed with a rigid collar.
An airway must be provided and the patient must be placed on his back to drain fluid from the lungs.
It should not be held by the legs and dangled to drain the water.
No attempt should be made to correct the deformity of the patient's neck.
The cervical vertebrae may be fractured.
However, if the spinal cord has not yet been damaged, first aid and improper positioning of the neck during patient transport can cause broken bone fragments to press on the spinal cord and cut and damage it.
Provence lavender is threatened by climate change
It's become a symbol of Provence in southern France, but there's a warning that it's under threat from climate change.
Lavender is in decline because of drought-like conditions and disease-carrying insects, causing a major headache for scientists and farmers trying to find a solution.
Eric Chaisse, an expert at CRIEPPAM, an agricultural research institute in Provence, said: "Lavender in Provence is effectively endangered because in recent years the plant has been exposed to the effects of climate change, which brings much less rain in spring and mostly in autumn.
It affects the life of the lavender.
There is also a small cicada, a leaf pest that transmits microorganisms, and they are abundant in very dry weather".
And a lot is at stake.
In addition to attracting vacationers, lavender oil is highly sought after for perfumes and cosmetics.
Eric Chaisse said: "Where there should be very tall plants with a few large flowers, we have smaller, underdeveloped or nonexistent or weak spikes.
So we have less of the fatty parts".
Solutions under consideration include better water distribution and slowing evaporation from the soil, but also spraying plants with a protective mud-and-water mixture and developing drought-tolerant varieties.
