But on this day, in the shadow of their own tragedy, they came together to discuss their safety.
They were told it was important to change their routine.
Two senior journalists discuss what makes them feel safer: bringing their children with them to the office that was targeted by a grenade in 2009, or leaving them at home.
Security experts wrote three words on the blackboard in front of the room: adversaries, neutrals, allies.
They ask reporters to suggest names for each column; no evidence is needed, just perceptions and gut feelings.
Drug traffickers, politicians, businessmen, journalists suspected of being on the payroll of the government or cartels, a list full of bad guys who make it dangerous to cover Mexico's chaos.
As the violence continues and the body count rises across the country, more and more of them are journalists: at least 25 have died since President Enrique Pena Nieto took office in December 2012, according to the Committee to Protect Journalists; 589 are under federal protection after attacks and threats; and at least seven have died in seven states so far this year.
Among the latest to die is Javier Valdez Cardenas, editorial director and co-founder of the inspirational Riodoce.
"The biggest mistake is to live in Mexico and be a journalist", writes Valdez in one of his many books on drug violence.
His absence is deeply felt but his presence is everywhere, with a large photo of Valdez showing his middle finger and the word "Justice" hanging on the facade of Riodoce's building; two reporters in their 30s, Aaron Ibarra and Miriam Ramirez, wear T-shirts showing his smile, glasses and his trademark Panama hat.
The workshop takes place less than two months after her death, and the reporters talk about their shared trauma, nightmares, insomnia, paranoia.
Although a special federal prosecutor's office was created in 2010 to handle journalists' cases, it has prosecuted only two, according to the Committee to Protect Journalists.
As with many of the thousands of murders linked to drug trafficking and organized crime each year, the killers of journalists are rarely brought to justice.
In Rio de Janeiro, although their hearts are broken, although the ground is now more treacherous, they insist on referring to the violence in Sinaloa.
Without information about the killers, without justice, negotiating security is of little use, says Ibarra.
He says, "It's stupid to waste my time in this workshop".
"You don't trust anyone until we know why".
On the morning of May 15, Valdez left Riodoce's office in the state capital of Culiacan.
