But there's been almost nothing but silence about Valdez.
Since Guzman's arrest last year and extradition to the US in January, Sinaloa has become one of the country's bloodiest battlegrounds as rival groups battle to fill the void.
Never mind that one or more people are shot and killed on the streets of Sinaloa every day, or that the cemetery is filled with ornate, two-story mausoleums of drug lords larger than most people's homes.
Forget for a minute the "calm" that only one cartel controls valuable ports and drug trafficking routes into the United States.
Despite this, and despite being deeply aware of the dangers of Valdez's work, Ismail Bojorquez, 60, co-founder and director of Riodoce, was wracked with guilt for failing to protect his friend.
He believes two mistakes contributed to the murder.
First, a February broadcast featured an interview with Damaso Lopez, leader of one of the rival cartel groups at war with Guzman's sons.
This article may have angered the sons; potential gang members bought every copy of the edition as soon as it was distributed to newsstands.
The second mistake was not forcing Valdez to leave the country for his own safety after another newspaper with the same story was seized.
Valdez was a legend in Mexico and abroad, and his murder was seen as a turning point in Mexican-originated violence against journalists.
He had survived so long, his friends and colleagues assumed he would always be there.
He was an experienced reporter in the Northeast in 2013 when he joined five colleagues in unveiling Riodoce by selling $50 shares.
In Sinaloa, "it was impossible to do journalism without talking about drugs", Bojorquez said.
In time, the paper gained a reputation for bold and honest reporting, and sales and advertising increased.
Reporters loved publishing vital investigations without fear of censorship, and readers were drawn to a publication where they could read stories that no one else dared to cover.
Eight years after its founding, Riodoce won the prestigious Maria Moors Cabot Prize for its reporting in Latin America.
That same year, Valdez won the International Press Freedom Award from the Committee to Protect Journalists for having the courage to pursue the Mexican drug story wherever it leads.
He openly admitted he was scared.
During the CPJ awards, he said, "I want to go on living".
In an interview with Rompeviento TV, he said that drug trafficking in Sinaloa is "a way of life".
"As a journalist, you have to accept your role, or play the fool.
