The dinosaur used camouflage to avoid its enemies.
At first glance, it looks like a statue, but it's a terrible one.
Researchers now report that the first findings of an incredible rhino-sized creature found by a Canadian miner are so well preserved that experts have described it as the 'Mona Lisa of dinosaurs.'
It was so well preserved that they could tell that the skin of the scales was reddish brown and that it had a 'troubled past.'
The report in the journal Current Biology described it as "the best-preserved armored dinosaur ever found and one of the best preserved dinosaur genera in the world".
The fossil is a newly discovered species of nodosaur that lived from the mid-Cretaceous Period, 110 million to 112 million years ago.
Its remarkably well-preserved condition has baffled researchers, who describe it as 'truly remarkable.'
The herbivorous armadillo is the best preserved fossil of its kind ever found, according to reports in National Geographic.
It was discovered by Shawn Funk on March 21, 2011, while excavating the Suncor Millennium Mine near Fort McMurray in Northern Alberta, Canada.
He hit something that looked strange compared to the surrounding rock and decided to take a closer look.
The fossil was sent to the Royal Tyrrell Museum of Palaeontology.
They spent the next six years unearthing the wild animal from a 2,500-pound (1,100 kg) mound of earth.
After such intensive work, the finished result is now ready to be presented.
Lead author Caleb Brown, a scientist at the Royal Tyrrell Museum, where the creature is on display, said: 'If you squint a little, you can almost believe it's asleep.'
'It will go down in the history of science as one of the most beautiful and best preserved dinosaur specimens, the Mona Lisa of dinosaurs.'
By examining its skin, researchers found that although it was covered in armor and looked like a walking tank, this plant-eater likely faced a serious threat from meat-eating dinosaurs.
Heavily armoured, the dinosaur used red and white camouflage to hide from predators and employed a protective technique known as countershading, used by many modern animals.
Experts suggest it was hunted by larger dinosaurs, allowing it to blend in better and evade predators.
The 110-million-year-old creature from the nodosaur family first made headlines in May and is now on display at the Royal Tyrrell Museum of Palaeontology.
The researchers have now completed their work and have named the wild animal Borealopelta markmitchelli after Mark Mitchell, a museum technician who was part of the team that painstakingly spent more than 7,000 hours unearthing it.
The extraordinary preservation of the species has allowed Dr. Mitchell and his international team of scientists to document the pattern and shape of the scales and the body armor.
They discovered countershading, a common defense mechanism in the animal kingdom, which means that the top of the creature is darker than the bottom.
Although countershading is common, the findings are surprising because the size of the Borealopelta far exceeds that of any countershading animals alive today.
This suggests that the dinosaur was sufficiently oppressed and hunted by carnivorous dinosaurs that evolution chose hiding over confrontation as a method of survival.
But most modern animals that use countershading (such as deer, zebras, or armadillos) are much smaller and much more likely to be prey, meaning that this nodosaur faced a serious challenge to its survival.
'The powerful hunting of a huge, heavily armoured animal shows just how dangerous dinosaur predators in the Cretaceous could be,' said Brown.
Chemical analysis of the organic compounds in the scales also revealed that the dinosaur's skin was reddish brown.
Scientists continue to study the animal for clues about its life, including preserved gut contents, to find out what it ate for its last meal.
They believe that when the dinosaur died, it fell into a river and was swept out to sea, where it sank on its back to the surface of the ocean.
At that time, Alberta was as warm as South Florida is today, and rivers and oceans probably extended farther inland than they do now.
