How did an activist come to learn the answer to the question, "Whose streets?"
On August 9, 2014, Brittany Ferrell was deeply shaken.
The day after arriving in New York City for a visit, the St. Louis native sat down on the bed of her Airbnb rental and started scrolling through Facebook on her phone.
It's a match to someone from high school.
It said, "Police just killed an 18-year-old kid, and he's still lying in the street".
Surprised that no one else in his feed shared this information, he closed Facebook and opened Twitter.
A user named @TheePharoah was constantly being retweeted in his feed.
The rapper from the St. Louis area was live-tweeting the death of Michael Brown, the 18-year-old who was shot and killed by an unarmed black police officer in Ferguson, Missouri.
He shared a photo of Brown's lifeless body lying in the street for four hours.
Ferrell thought to himself, "This is wild".
But death was not new to him or to his people.
He left his phone to return to tweeting about people gathering on Canfield Drive later that evening.
There were police tapes, people screaming, and photos of a man claiming to be Brown's father holding a sign that said, "Ferguson police just killed my unarmed son!"
He watched a live broadcast of a police officer standing in front of a group of protesters with a barking dog.
In another video, another officer, he said, cocked the trigger of his rifle and shouted, "I'll kill you all... animals".
Ferrell recalled him saying, "'That's unusual.'"
"'This is not the kind of murder we're used to, nor is it typical.
At that moment, I felt a chill.
I was angry and crying".
He booked a return ticket and went home the next day.
After landing at 11 p.m., she picked up her 6-year-old daughter from her father's house and decided to drive to Ferguson with her the next morning.
What happened to Ferrell and Ferguson over the next three years is the subject of a new documentary, "Whose Streets?" Coming to theaters August 11.
This is a story of survival and protest, love and loss, power and resistance from the perspective of the people who live in that community and fill the streets with the answers they seek.
As Ferrell drove his car to Ferguson with his daughter, who was wearing a floral dress and a matching tiara, they returned to the conversation "about the black experience and the black condition" they had had many times before that morning.
"Remember when I taught you that black people should fight for what they believe in?"
"We're going to Ferguson right now because the police killed an 18-year-old kid, and it wasn't right.
I couldn't not take it", Ferrell said later.
"What is happening here today... is the result of what happened in the past.
He must know it, see it, and grow into it.
Not only do we need to become better at activism and organizing, but we need to know the layers of the black experience and the black condition and what we need to do to liberate, to liberate ourselves.
Even if I'm lucky enough to give her an experience where she doesn't experience crude racism firsthand, she's no different than any other black woman-child.
I feel like I'm hurting her by protecting her from all of this".
When they arrived in Ferguson, their first stop was on South Florissant Road, which had become something of a campground for activists, across from police headquarters, where they waited to talk about the issue that later resulted in Officer Darren Wilson not being charged.
There, Ferrell and her daughter contacted local business owners who prepared packaged food.
They packed bags and helped deliver them to the protesters.
For Ferrell, a new kind of activism was slowly taking shape.
"My activism was completely transformed after August 9th", she said, noting that while a student at Missouri State University, she was president of the Minority Student Nurses Association and focused on food justice and health inequity in the black community.
"I had no experience in organizing.
It just came to me".
Weeks later, Ferrell met one of the film's co-directors, Sabaah Folayan, at an evening screening.
Folayan said he and his director of photography, Lucas Alvarado-Farrar, "wanted to document" what was happening.
A question came to Ferrell's mind: "Do you want to document or do you want to find a story you can use?"
This skepticism has been voiced by countless individuals in countless situations, usually white, who have come to a community to profit from its pain and its resistance...
As Folayan explained in a recent interview, "We had heard that the voices of people born and raised in Ferguson couldn't be condensed, and we decided to do it differently".
Folayan had already contacted co-director Damon Davis, a local artist known for his activism on behalf of death row inmates.
His involvement warmed Ferrell to the project, which the "Whose Streets?" team followed in the years after Brown's shooting, along with six other area natives.
"This is not a documentary in which someone speaks for us or to us", said David.
"That's what was important to me, how these people were going to be represented because that's how I was going to be represented".
Folayan said, "While the intention was not to focus on Ferrell's experiences, he proved to be the most outspoken of the film's participants, as he demonstrated that the movement is "not about a messianic leader, it's about community coming together".
As a result, "Whose Streets?" surprisingly documents personal aspects of Ferrell's life, such as falling in love and marrying his wife.
Laughing at his first glimpse of the finished product, Ferrell said, "I felt naked".
"But in doing this work and in humanizing black people, I realized there could be some sensitivity".
Ferrell's story also solidifies and re-centers the role of black lesbians in the Black Lives Matter movement.
Two of the three founders of the movement, which derived the slogan #BlackLivesMatter from social media following the 2012 murder of black teenager Trayvon Martin, identify as gay.
"Black lesbians in leadership have generally kept the movement alive", Ferrell said, "and that's because we're constantly at war on many fronts.
Black lesbians have to bear the brunt of it".
Folayan agreed, stating, "The movement is really sustained by black women and many gay black women".
However, Ferrell insists that "this is not some sort of affirmative action" and that he was not chosen because of his identity.
"He was the one who set the energy in motion", she says.
"But it's no accident that she's on the front lines, because as a black lesbian woman, you have a lot to lose by living a life at these intersections.
You can feel his energy through the screen".
Meanwhile, in Ferguson, news cameras are long gone, but troubling racial connections remain between the community and the police.
Ferrell's on probation for another two and a half years for blocking a highway during a demonstration.
He describes the socio-political atmosphere in the area he calls home as "chaotic".
And yet, Ferguson holds on to the song he wrote in his head three years before he hit the streets.
"It is our duty to fight for our freedom.
It's our duty to win.
We have to love and support each other.
We have nothing to lose but our chains".
