The artist uses Chelsea Manning's DNA to create portraits
In the middle of the room at the Friedman Gallery in New York, there are many faces, white, black and brown, hanging from wires in the ceiling, each of which bears an almost unmistakable resemblance to the other.
These 30 portraits were created by artist Heather Dewey-Hagborg from ear sticks and cropped hair sent to her by Chelsea Manning.
Manning, a former intelligence analyst serving a 35-year sentence for leaking classified diplomatic cables through the website WikiLeaks, famously sent his cropped hair from Fort Leavenworth prison.
The new exhibit, which opens August 2nd, is called A Suitable Similitude.
It's the product of two years of correspondence between Dewey-Hagborg, who combined her discipline with expertise in technology, computer science and the arts, and Manning, a trans woman and leading dissident whose sentence was commuted by Barack Obama three days before she left office.
By algorithmically analyzing the DNA extracted from Manning and creating 30 portraits using what a person with this gene data might look like, Dewey-Hagborg revealed not only the tractability of the DNA data (that there are many ways it can be interpreted and the inherent determinism of interpretations) but also its identity with a rigorous, perhaps somewhat cerebral interpretation.
Manning, who was born Bradley Edward but openly identified as a woman as a teenager, was convicted in 2013 of 20 charges, including six under the Espionage Act, computer fraud and theft.
His image was suppressed by the prison, so that he had only one photograph: a gritty, black-and-white selfie of a visibly agitated Manning sitting in the driver's seat, wearing a platinum-yellow wig that matched his own.
In 2015, Dewey-Hagborg was enjoying success with the massive success of her 2012 project Stranger Things.
In it, the artist produced portraits by scraping DNA from forensic debris like cigarette butts and chewing gum to paint a picture of what these people might have looked like.
That's when he got an e-mail from Paper Magazine.
"They were doing an interview with Chelsea Manning when she was in prison, and they wanted some kind of portrait that could accompany this article", Dewey-Hagborg explained at a press preview of the new exhibit.
She couldn't be visited or photographed during that time, so they reached out to Chelsea and asked if she'd be interested in having a DNA profile done.
The artist and his imprisoned muse exchanged many letters over the course of two years, becoming unlikely pen pals.
They even produced Printed Images, a cartoon book illustrated by Shoili Kanungo, in which the president pardoned Chelsea's sentence and imagined a future in which she could see the exhibition in person.
The fact that Obama actually called for Manning's release just days after the book came out was a kind of happy coincidence that came after seven brutal years in a military prison in Kansas.
As Donald Trump wages war on government whistleblowers and transgender troops and finds new, tweetable ways to further fuel the sharp divisions he's been asked to heal, there's something deep and powerful about this exhibition opening right now.
When asked about the odd timing of all this, Dewey-Hagborg said, "Things happen for a reason".
An artist statement written on the gallery wall, with Manning's oversized signature beneath it (the "i" in her last name is dotted with a heart), called for an end to "automatic discrimination" based on "gender, race, sexuality and culture".
Across the wall is his mitochondrial DNA sequence: lots of C's, G's and A's written in pencil...
By including 200 letters (or nucleotides, according to the artist's sophisticated scientific dictionary), Dewey Hagborg wanted to convey how amazingly similar we all are, at least as biological creatures.
"What I hope people take away from this is that our genome doesn't care about who we are and how open to interpretation the genetic data is, how subjective it is", said Dewey-Hagborg, who was exhibiting her video work Simulated Memories in 2007.
"DNA data can tell many different stories, and this is 30 of them".
The final piece in the exhibit, which is housed in a single room, is a page from the aforementioned short comic book.
Here's Manning walking out of the United States Disciplinary Barracks, King Kong style, with a speaker in his hand.
It says, "When they shut you down, they win".
"So never shut up".
The artist from Philadelphia said, "This came directly from a letter he wrote me".
"I still get goosebumps when I talk about it".
Manning has not yet seen the exhibit in person (as he rather presciently imagined from the comic book), but when he does he will be greeted by masks, which are genetic replicas of himself, gathered in the middle of the room like a group of protesters.
Like everything in the exhibit, the genetic haplogroups were written in pencil up to Manning's height (5'2, Manning's height), which was done specifically.
Dewey-Hagborg said of the portraits, "In the past I would have put them on the wall but I wanted them to feel like a crowd".
"I wanted it to be perceived as a collective movement that was taking shape with Chelsea, as well as the movement behind her release".
