Russian Deputy Prime Minister Vitaly Mutko has said that it will not take long for the Russian Anti-Doping Agency (RUSADA) to implement the remaining World Anti-Doping Agency (WADA) criteria to become operational again.
"A certain stage in the fulfillment of the roadmap criteria has been completed, RUSADA has obtained the right to plan and test in cooperation with UKAD (United Kingdom Anti-Doping).
The WADA roadmap has been updated in this context", Mutko said on Thursday.
The Prime Minister was reviewing the second part of the WADA Regulatory Compliance Roadmap, recently published on the institution's website, which outlines the criteria governing RUSADA's re-operation.
According to Mutko, it doesn't contain anything that would concern Russia.
"Everything has been announced, everything will be implemented.
The results will be presented to the International Olympic Committee [IOC] and WADA in the near future".
However, one criterion mentioned in the list states that Russian anti-doping authorities must publicly acknowledge the reported results of a WADA-approved alleged state-sponsored doping investigation into Russian sport conducted by Canadian lawyer Richard McLaren.
Referring to the issue, Mutko said: "While our anti-doping system admits a failure, we are also conducting the investigation.
All precautions have been taken.
But there is no state program, and we will not accept something that does not exist".
Mutko's words echoed those of Vitaly Smirnov, head of the Russian Independent Public Anti-Doping Commission.
Speaking to Russian broadcaster RSport earlier in the day, Smirnov acknowledged past problems with Russia's anti-doping bodies but added: "We have said on many occasions that the report contains contradictory positions and regulations.
No one intends to accept the report unconditionally", Smirnov added.
RUSADA was suspended by WADA from conducting doping controls in Russia in November 2005 following a doping scandal.
However, under the supervision of international experts and UK Anti-Doping (UKAD), this June testing was allowed to be planned and coordinated.
