A new kind of human resources start-up is emerging to help companies understand how their employees feel.
They produce and license software specifically designed to measure employee engagement, allowing companies to conduct multiple-choice surveys, target specific teams and demographic groups, offer employees anonymity and complaint hotlines, and in some cases allow employees to bypass senior management and go directly to the board of directors to report a malfunction.
Jim Barnett, co-founder and president of Glint, a Redwood City start-up that measures employee engagement through software analytics tools provided by companies, said, "There are now tools like Strava and Fitbit that track your health, but where is your company's Fitbit?"
Errett says that by using Glint, he has a better understanding of what his employees are thinking and feeling three years later.
It offers quick surveys and multiple-choice surveys to specific teams, as well as a heat map showing at a glance which departments of the company receive the most complaints and which managers have low approval ratings, so that the reasons for these can be tampered with.
Companies are beginning to understand that to avoid becoming the next Uber, they need to be knowledgeable about their workplace culture; Uber has been in a scandal ever since a former employee posted a blog post describing a harassment environment where those who openly say what they think are punished.
For startups like Glint, this demand for oversight means a very lucrative business opportunity.
According to financial technology insights website Let's Talk Payments, the global governance, regulation and compliance industry could be worth $118.7 billion by 2020.
Interest and activity in Convercent, a Denver Colorado-based start-up that helps companies detect and prevent bad behavior, increased amid controversy over Uber's discrediting earlier this year.
Convercent has close to 600 clients, including Airbnb, Microsoft and Tesla.
Uber recently signed on as a client.
Like Glint, Convercent allows companies to conduct personalized "pulse" polls, collect real-time confidential responses, and generate heat maps of problem areas.
It also offers an anonymous tip line where employees can report misconduct.
If the president is accused, complaints go directly to the board.
Patrick Quinlan, founder and president of Covercent, said, "The court of public opinion has captured the regulators".
Quinlan said that if a company mistreats its employees or behaves unethically, it can face costly consequences from consumer boycotts, employee layoffs, or lawsuits, even if regulators don't step in.
Ruby Tuesday, a restaurant chain with more than 25,000 employees in 500 locations, has been using Convercent for more than a year to keep its employees informed of policies and procedures and to provide easy access to company headquarters.
Previously, when an employee wanted to report a problem, he or she had to find a phone number or an e-mail address associated with company headquarters, make a formal complaint, and hope that it would be taken seriously.
James Vitrano, Ruby Tuesday's chief legal counsel, said these were often intimidating and uncomfortable experiences, not a good way to follow up on employee complaints.
But now that the company is using Convercent, problems that were previously hidden from executives sitting across an office, city, or state - such as discrimination, harassment, or unfair pay practices - can be identified and resolved faster.
Vitrano, who leads Ruby Tuesday's risk management group, said, "I can approach this employment experience with a more holistic, 360-degree view".
"We also protect our shareholders from corporate lawsuits".
After the collapse of accounting firm Arthur Andersen in 2002 due to ethics violations stemming from the Enron scandal, companies took ethics, values, and employee relations more seriously in 2002, Quinlan said.
But after "social media came to life", companies realized they couldn't keep their dirty laundry from going viral.
He said, "Before technology was used to control ethics, people used hope as a strategy".
Both Glint and Convercent offer their software as a service and charge recurring fees for use of their products.
It's a business model and opportunity that's been validated by the venture capitalists who back both startups.
Convercent received $10 million in funding in February from firms including Sapphire Ventures and Tola Capital, bringing its total capital raised to $47 million.
Glint raised $10 million from Bessemer Venture Partners in November, bringing its total funding to $60 million.
Given the interconnected nature of companies, their cultures, and their need for venture capital, these investments are hardly surprising.
A growing body of research shows that today's employees expect more from their workplaces than ever before.
In competitive markets like Silicon Valley, high salaries and interesting projects are just minimum requirements.
Employees want to feel accepted, valued, and that they're giving their time to a company with a positive mission.
Nina McQueen, LinkedIn's vice president of global benefits and employee experience, who uses both Convercent and Glint, said, "When people are happy to be at a company, when they feel their voices are heard, and their work is satisfying, they are more invested in making that company successful".
Investors make money when their portfolio companies do well; companies do well when their employees are genuine and feel a sense of belonging.
If third-party analytics tools promise to increase employee authenticity and sense of belonging, it's not surprising that they find support.
Having data on employee engagement is important to workplace culture experts.
But the data is useless if the people in charge of the company don't act.
In fact, if a company asks for feedback from its employees, it can create an expectation that change is coming.
And if that expectation isn't met quickly enough or at all, it can lead to frustration and make employees feel disconnected.
Russell Raath, who's the head of consulting at Kotter International, a management consulting firm, saw that companies make the mistake of relying too much on data collection, and he said, "If you're going to ask for 4,000 suggestions, you need to be prepared to have 4,000 conversations".
"Because if you don't follow up, employees will think, 'Did you really hear me?
Do you care?
And if you don't care, why should I?'"
According to Errett, Madison Reed, who conducts monthly employee surveys, was able to take action the same day a problem was reported at Glint.
And after gathering feedback from employees who were tired of the speed of decision-making and the quality of communication, he was able to reorganize various teams within the company and add communication training to help solve problems.
At Ruby Tuesday, the company is gaining new insights into its own employees, and hopes that in the long run, this will translate into being able to retain more workers in this type of industry, which is known to have high employee turnover.
Vitrona said, "If you're not committed to creating a culture of transparency, you're going to lose people".
"And if you lose people, you're going to lose customers.
And when you lose customers, you're going to lose businesses".
