Facebook increases its story verification power to fight fake news
Facebook will send more potentially fake articles to third-party story verifiers and show their findings below the original post, the world's largest online social network said Thursday as it tries to combat so-called fake news.
In a statement on the firm's website, they said they would use updated machine learning to detect possible hoaxes and send them to story verifiers, potentially showing the story verification results below the original article.
Facebook has been criticized for being one of the main distribution points for so-called fake news, which many believe influenced the 2016 U.S. presidential election.
The issue has also become a major political topic in Europe, with French voters facing a flood of fake news ahead of the presidential election in May and Germany backing a plan to fine social media networks if they fail to quickly remove hateful posts ahead of elections there in September.
On Thursday, Facebook said in a separate statement in German that a test of the new story verification feature was being launched in the United States, France, the Netherlands, and Germany.
Sara Su, Facebook's news feed product manager, said in a blog post: "In addition to seeing what stories are being discussed by third-party story verifiers, people want more sources about what they're reading and sharing to make informed decisions".
He added that Facebook will continue to test the "related article" feature and work on other changes to the news feed to reduce fake news.
Creating comics: the story of a castle in England
In its recent past, tiny Scotney Castle was featured in a Squeeze music video and was a refuge for Margaret Thatcher in the 1970s and 1980s.
But now, inspired by a comic book written by Jamie Rhodes, a broom-haired Yorkshireman with a passion for historical documentation, Scotney has witnessed 700 years of turbulent history from his comfortable seat in the valley of the River Bewl in Kent.
"I think it's beautiful to look at the handwriting of someone who's been dead for 300 years", he says wistfully.
"What a personal connection it is to hold this letter in my hand".
Spanning from the Edwardian era to the Middle Ages, A Castle in England documents families who lived in Scotney, with each story being painted by a different named artist from the United Kingdom (Isaac Lenkiewicz, Briony May Smith, William Exley, Becky Palmer, and Isabel Greenberg).
This is not Rhodes' first book based on an archive: she also wrote 2014's Dead Men's Teeth and Other Stories, a project she found unexpectedly emotional, inspired by stories in the British Library.
"I've even had my eyes gouged out by a fingerprint on the side of a letter written in the 1700s by a double agent working for the King James supporters".
"That was his thumbprint!
And the letters always stink because back then you had a fire for light.
To someone 300 years in the future, the smell makes him feel like he's there.
Oh, I like the archives!"
As someone who loves old papers, having support from the National Trust and Arts Council England and being able to spend almost four months in a castle ("To be honest, I overstayed my welcome by staying a little longer than I should have") seems too good.
Rhodes spent his days exploring the "new" Victorian-era castle, combing through archives, and studying its many treasures and antiques, such as hyena heads mounted on the mansion's walls and bottles that had spent centuries in ditches.
He toured the grounds and ruins of the old castle, talking to rangers, gardeners, and sometimes artists working on his book's illustrations.
Then at night, he would "drink whiskey and write".
Scotney's detailed history is relatively unknown, as the National Trust only gained full access when the last heiress, Elizabeth Hussey, died in 2006.
When Rhodes arrived ten years later, the staff had barely begun to handle the archive, which he describes as "centuries of aristocrats saying, 'Oh, throw him in the attic.'"
Diaries, letters from the days of the British empire, maps marking the boundaries of who owned what: "You'd think land disputes would be boring", says Rhodes, "but there was a birch tree over which two families fought.
Forget about it, man!"
Some stories in the collection use the castle as a jumping-off point for a broader introduction to English history, including The Labourer, who leaves the newly built castle to join the Peasants' Revolt of 1381.
"In this book, The Knights Families of Kent and Sussex, there is a record of a rebellion at the castle in 1380", says Rhodes.
"The Peasants' Revolt had started nearby and I thought a revolt would be a good place to start.
Maybe the two are connected?"
Other stories are closely linked to the history of the castle, such as The Priest, which tells the story of the Darrell family who hid a Jesuit priest for 7 years during the English Reformation.
Or The Smuggler, featuring 18th-century smuggler Arthur Darrell, who allegedly stuffed a coffin with stones and staged his own funeral (a revelation made years later when his coffin was exhumed).
The Darrells are Rhodes' favourite Scotney family: "These gentlemen seemed to be pretty crooked, always getting into debt and spending money on things they couldn't afford.
Over the generations, Darrell men have solved their debt crises by marrying rich older women; I imagine them as a bunch of handsome men with a knack for wooing heiresses".
Rhodes, having completed his tour of duty at the fort, seeks other singular writing experiences.
In Finnish wildlife, he completed a two-week assignment for a comic about Elämänmäki, the site of a sanatorium in the early 20th century, which has since been reclaimed by nature.
But Scotney holds a special place in her heart.
She says, "I was sad to leave".
"It's like, 'Oh, now I have to go and face fucking reality.'"
