Around Christmas and Thanksgiving, newspapers across the United States were filled with how to deal with the nightmare of relatives voting for Trump.
We all strive to burst our so-called filter bubbles.
Less talked about is Trump's ability to bring families together.
I mention this because my cousin, a left-leaning poet who lives in Chicago and has had a falling out with the Republicans in our family, is visiting us in New York this week.
It reminded me that uniting against a common enemy can have a powerful effect.
With Trump in the White House, everyone he knows, including his Republican brother with whom he's argued about policy for decades, is suddenly and strangely on the same side.
That's a good thing at the dinner table, of course, but it seems to me that in a broader context, it carries significant risks.
The left has been reinvigorated by Trump, but the bending effect of his presidency has created a push to the right for all of us.
When we talk about "normalization" and Trump, we're talking about the terrifying possibility that one day his bizarre behavior will no longer be shocking.
There's an even more frightening long-term scenario in which Trump "normalizes" right-wing Republicans who defy his standards and suddenly seem like the epitome of sanity.
I find myself nostalgic for Mitt Romney's bizarre version of insanity these days: the dog on the roof of the car, the 14% income tax (but at least we knew what his tax return looked like), both of which are really very minor offenses according to Trump.
When Trump is gone, the next Republican nominee only needs to be sane to be judged to have made immeasurable progress.
