Red meat, dairy products, and chocolate may alleviate IBS
Red meat and chocolate may sound like a nightmare for your digestive system.
But a new study suggests just the opposite: A diet rich in meat-based protein and dairy products may help alleviate the symptoms of those who suffer from inflammatory bowel disease.
This incurable medical condition, which affects 1.3 million people in the United States and 300,000 in the United Kingdom, causes stomach cramps and bloating, recurrent or bloody diarrhea, weight loss, and extreme fatigue.
Although patients are often advised to avoid meat and dairy products to alleviate their symptoms, researchers at the University of Washington found that the protein's essential amino acid tryptophan aids the development of immune cells that develop a resilient gut.
Lead researcher Dr. Marco Colonna explained that immune cells patrol the intestines to prevent foodborne germs from sneaking into the body.
Cells capable of triggering inflammation are balanced by cells that promote endurance, protecting delicate tissue from damage.
If the balance shifts too much towards inflammation, inflammation can result in bowel disease.
In experiments, mice carrying a specific bacterium in their gut were found to produce a type of immune cell that promotes endurance.
And bacteria need tryptophan, one of the building blocks of protein, to trigger the emergence of cells.
Professor Colonna said: 'We have established a link between Lactobacillus reuteri, a bacterial species that is part of the gut microbiome, and the development of a cell population that promotes resistance.'
Mice with more tryptophan in their diets had more of these immune cells".
If the same thing happens in humans, he suggested, a diet rich in L. reuteri and tryptophan could promote a more resilient, less inflammatory gut environment.
Her postdoctoral researcher, Dr. Luisa Cervantes-Barraganwas, was working on a type of immune cell that promotes resilience when she discovered that one group of lab mice had these types of cells, but another group of the same species kept in a different location did not.
He suspected that the difference had to do with the gut microbiomes of the mice, in other words, the communities of bacteria, viruses and fungi that normally live in the gastrointestinal tract.
They sequenced the DNA of the guts of the mice, and they found that the mice that had immune cells had six types of bacteria, but the mice that didn't have immune cells didn't have any.
Mice that lacked a gut microbiome and did not develop this type of immune cell because they were looked after in a sterile environment were given L. reuteri and immune cells emerged.
To understand how the bacterium affects the immune system, researchers grew L. reuteri in liquid and then transferred small amounts of this liquid, which is free of bacteria, into immature immune cells taken from mice.
Immune cells turned into cells that promote endurance.
The active ingredient, when purified from the liquid, turned out to be a byproduct of tryptophan metabolism known as indole-3-lactic acid.
When the researchers doubled the amount of tryptophan in the mice's diet, the number of cells increased by about 50 percent, but when the tryptophan levels were halved, the number of cells dropped by half.
Dr. Cervantes-Barragan stated that humans have the same resistance-promoting cells as mice, and most of us harbor L. reuteri in our gastrointestinal tract.
It is not known whether tryptophan byproducts from L. reuteri develop in humans as they do in mice, but defects in tryptophan-related genes have been found in people with inflammatory bowel disease.
He said: "The development of these cells is something we probably want to encourage because these cells control inflammation in the inner surface of the intestines.
Potentially in cases where L. reuteri is present, high levels of tryptophan cause this population to spread".
