The White House show cost the taxpayers thousands.
According to military records released to TIME, the White House's decision last month to fly a Marine helicopter over the south lawn for an event highlighting American manufacturing cost taxpayers up to $24,000.
When the president boarded, the green and white Sikorsky VH-3D, also known as Marine One, was the focus of attention at the July 17 White House launch of American construction programs.
President Donald Trump, Vice President Mike Pence and senior White House officials toured products manufactured in all 50 states.
It was displayed alongside a helicopter from Connecticut, a yacht from Maine, a fire truck from Wisconsin, and a forklift from Mississippi.
According to the records of Marine Helicopter Squadron One (HMX-1), the unit responsible for operating the helicopter; the White House War Room requested the helicopter's presence by an individual order (also called FRAGO) only 36 hours before the helicopter landed on the south lawn for "unusual" organization.
The commander of HMX-1 sent an email to his superior, the Deputy Commandant of Marine Corps Aviation, the day before the event, saying, "I just wanted to make sure you were aware because this is an unusually high-visibility organization".
The message stated that the helicopter would arrive on the south lawn around 7 a.m. on July 17 for the 3 p.m. event and would remain there until the lawn was cleared between 6 and 9 p.m.
The memo added that if the departure from the White House was delayed, a second flight crew would be required for the return flight due to duty time limitations.
While unit security personnel stood inside the aircraft while it was on the ground, the original flight crew was in the helicopter during the event.
It is unclear from the recordings provided to TIME whether a second flight crew was ultimately necessary.
The Hatch Act prohibits federal employees from using government property for political purposes.
Records show that HMX-1 investigated whether the organization violated that provision.
The commander wrote, "One question we asked was whether he had violated the Hatch Act, and we were told he had not".
"Looks like you're locked out", the XO replied.
The "Made in America" organization is designated by the White House as an official organization and is not subject to the Hatch Act.
But even formal organizations have political implications.
At the event, the president referred to the healthcare reform efforts underway in the senate at the time and praised efforts to rein in government regulations.
The use of aircraft known as Marine One or Air Force One for politically advantageous purposes is not a new phenomenon.
Presidents are supposed to use them to travel.
But it's unusual to be officially asked to use them just for a photo opportunity.
Trump gained attention in February when Air Force One went behind the scenes of his first campaign rally in Melbourne, Florida, and his Twitter account was flooded with messages about his predecessor's use of Air Force One.
White House deputy press secretary Lindsay Walters said: "The White House is excited about the 'Made in America' exhibit, with products made by American workers from all 50 states with American materials".
HMX-1 crews frequently conduct training flights over the Washington area and practice dropping the President of the United States on the South Lawn with a point-blank shot at the White House.
While Trump was in Germany for the G-20 summit in early July, HMX-1 conducted 58 practice landings at the White House.
An official said the flight for the Made in America organization was part of the aircrew's training needs for that month.
Unit helicopters flew an additional 11 hours that day for "non-presidential support missions".
The White House said taxpayers weren't charged for any other tricks involved in the organization.
A spokesman for Sikorksky said their company was not involved in arranging the display of the helicopter on the south lawn.
HMX-1 does not keep budget records for presidential flights, and it is difficult to determine the exact expense incurred by the organization.
But according to the DoD's hourly rates for fiscal year 2017, the DoD's VH-3D meet rate is $24,340 per flight hour.
Unit logs show the aircraft flew approximately 30 minutes each way from Marine Corps Air Facility Quantico, Virginia.
The White House claims that the actual operating cost of the helicopter is far less than that.
Walters said, "It's very misleading to taxpayers to base an expense on recovery rate estimates".
"These rate estimates include sunk costs in personnel, maintenance and annual expenses".
According to a 2015 RAND study, the Department of Defense's reimbursement rates do not include personnel costs but do include fuel, maintenance, and contract costs.
At the time, former White House press secretary Sean Spicer advocated the use of the helicopter for the event.
Spicer said, "The idea here is to showcase what's being done in America this week".
"And I know that Sikorsky and the state of Connecticut are very proud of their contribution to our national security, and I suspect that hundreds, if not thousands, of jobs depend on it.
And like most Americans, I think we're all very proud of the helicopters and other military equipment that many Americans have worked tirelessly to build.
So of course it's appropriate to highlight that".
It's unclear if Trump interacted with the helicopter as it circled the south lawn for the event, but he did step into the driver's seat of a fire truck.
Inside the White House, Trump addressed Sikorsky representatives, joking with the media about the company's products in his fleet.
The president said, "I know Sikorsky very well, I have three of them".
