GMB is concerned about McVitie's investment in the Glasgow plant.
A union is seeking assurances from the managers of biscuit maker McVitie's that they will be given a long-term commitment to production at its factory in Glasgow.
GMB Scotland said the company remained silent about the future of its investment in the Tollcross area.
More than 500 people work at the factory, which makes Hobnobs and Rich Tea biscuits, among other products.
Pladis, the owner of McVitie's, says they've invested more than £5 million in the area over the last few years.
He added that employees and union representatives would be "the first to know" if there was a change in their operations.
In a letter to the company's plant manager, GMB Scotland demanded that McVitie's "address its concerns that funding is not being provided for the modernisation of its production lines".
GMB senior organiser Drew Duffy said: "It is deeply concerning to our members that we are unable to see any clarity from the facility's general manager on business needs and the investment plan for the future of Tollcross.
Families have worked here for generations and the workforce is heavily concentrated in the local community and in Glasgow and its suburbs, a critical pillar of adequate employment in an area of high unemployment and social deprivation.
From a job, pay and welfare perspective, the circumstances of Brexit, rising costs of living and chronic production decline mean that there is an urgent need for a four-headed production presence at McVitie's in Glasgow's east end".
A spokeswoman for Pladis said: "The plant manager at Tollcross received a letter from GMB Scotland just yesterday and the company will respond directly as we value our commitment to workers and union representatives.
We had a regular meeting at Tollcross two months ago with employees and GMB representatives, where a number of issues were openly discussed.
At that time, we told our employees that, like all companies doing business in a highly competitive and uncertain economic environment, we were constantly reviewing our operations in order to remain competitive, which is true for all of our businesses and facilities.
He added: "We have invested more than £5 million in the Tollcross facility in recent years, particularly in production lines and operational improvements.
We fully recognize the heritage of Tollcross as a manufacturing facility, and if there are any changes to our operations at the facility, the employees and their union representatives will be the first to know".
